abstract = {The field activity patterns of Clethrionomys glareolus and Apodemus sylvaticus during the summer at an artificial feeding site are described. Apodemus, as expected, was nocturnal with a single major peak of activity. Clethrionomys, although recorded during each hour of the day, was predominantly diurnal with peaks of activity at dawn and dusk. This is in contrast to periods of activity throughout the twenty-four hours, with little indication of a diel preference, which have been shown in laboratory studies. The possibility that interspecific avoidance reactions affect their temporal patterns of activity is discussed},
